{
  "doc_id": "26325",
  "text": "and E7 proteins, which aid in tumorigenesis by altering cell cycle progression. HTLV-1 Tax has been shown to have a profound effect on the cell cycle, through a variety of mechanisms. Tax has been shown to induce hyperphosphorylation of Rb [CITATION_1] as well as transactivate the E2F-1 promoter [CITATION_2] . Therefore, it is not surprising that Tax can shorten the G 1 phase of the cell cycle with an early onset of cdk2 kinase activity [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Tax also has the ability to increase cdk4 associated kinase activity in HTLV-1 infected cells by binding to p16/INK4A, resulting in the inability of p16/INK4A to effectively inhibit cyclin D/ cdk4,6 complexes [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . The interaction of Tax with p16/INK4A does not fully account for the increased activity of cyclin D/cdk4,6 complexes, because cells null for p16/INK4A expression retain increased cdk4 kinase activity [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . More recently, Tax has also been shown to be able to directly bind to cdk4, resulting in increased cyclin D/cdk4 associated kinase activity [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] .",
